<div id="mntl-sc-block_2-0-28" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html">
<p>The video isn't the only thing that has changed with the DTV Transition, so has audio.</p>
</div>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_2-0-29" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html">
<p>Audio can be transmitted in two-channel <a href="https://www.lifewire.com/what-is-pcm-1846928" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">PCM</a> or in <a href="https://www.lifewire.com/dolby-digital-ex-plus-1846885" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Dolby Digital</a>, with support for up to 5.1 channels.</p>
</div>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_2-0-30" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html">
<p>This means that if a TV broadcast contains Dolby Digital 5.1 and the TV receiving the broadcast can pass the signal through a <a href="https://www.lifewire.com/digital-optical-connection-1846881" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">digital optical output</a> or <a href="https://www.lifewire.com/audio-return-channel-1846845" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">HDMI Return Channel</a> to a home theater receiver, you can listen to that TV broadcast in surround sound.</p>
</div>
<div id="mntl-sc-block_2-0-31" class="comp mntl-sc-block mntl-sc-block-html">
<p>However, it must be pointed out that the Dolby Digital pass-through option is provided at the TV maker's discretion.</p>
</div>
</div>
